{"type":"message","id":"ce4f1d50","parentId":"ad85cf59","timestamp":"2026-05-20T20:10:16.730Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The issue is that Python 3.12+ has a confusables policy that flags certain characters in source code. Let me check which characters are actually problematic:\n\nThe errors mention:\n1. U+2192 (→) - REPLACED with `->`\n2. U+3002 (。) - Ideographic full stop - this is being flagged\n\nActually, let me check if Python 3.14 actually has issues with these characters. The U+3002 (。) is used as a period in Chinese text, and it's inside string literals (docstrings). Python should accept this in strings.\n\nWait, let me re-read the error:\n\n\nThe error points to a `→` character at a specific position in the docstring, which shouldn't be there if I replaced all arrows with `->`. I need to check the file directly to see what's actually in the output.\n\nLooking at the hex dump more carefully, the arrow appears between \"器\" and \"yield\", but my previous fix should have replaced all instances. The issue might be that I wrote the file but the compilation check is still running against the old cached version. Let me verify by examining the actual bytes again to confirm whether the replacement actually took effect. I'm realizing the replacement was just executed, but the compilation check in the same script was using the old in-memory data before the file was written back to disk. I need to recompile the file after the write to get the actual result.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"...\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_7768e49e1f954af494a0fb1e","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python -c \"\npath = r'D:\\astro_py\\astro_hub\\src\\main\\main.py'\nwith open(path, 'rb') as f:\n    data = f.read()\n\n# Verify no arrow characters remain\narrow_count = data.count(b'\\xe2\\x86\\x92')\nprint('Arrow characters remaining: %d' % arrow_count)\n\n# Check line 78\nlines = data.split(b'\\r\\n